# Playwright Best Practices

> **Test runner:** This project uses **Playwright Test** (`@playwright/test`). Specs live in `tests/e2e/*.spec.ts` and use `test()` / `test.step()`. Page objects live in `pages/` and extend `BasePage` (`pages/base/BasePage.ts`). Shared fixtures (page objects + test data) are defined in `tests/base/baseTest.ts`. Note `testIdAttribute` is set to `"id"` in `playwright.config.ts`, so `getByTestId("foo")` matches `id="foo"`.

## 1. Use User-Facing Locators (Role-Based)

Prefer semantic, resilient locators. Avoid brittle CSS, dynamic IDs, and XPath.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
await page.getByRole("button", { name: "Submit" }).click();
await page.getByLabel("Email address").fill("test@example.com");
await page.getByPlaceholder("Search...").fill("query");
await page.getByText("Functional Testing").click();

// ❌ BAD
await page.locator("#submit-btn-123").click(); // dynamic/generated ID
await page.locator("div.form > input:nth-child(2)").fill("test"); // brittle CSS
await page.locator("xpath=..//div//div//div", { hasText: "msg" }); // XPath
```

### Exception: Generic `locator()` with Stable Selectors

When no built-in locator (`getByRole`, `getByLabel`, etc.) can reliably target an element, a `locator()` using a **stable** selector is acceptable. Some existing pages do this (e.g. `NavigationComponent` uses `#menu a` with `{ hasText }`, `BasePage` helpers accept CSS selector strings). Keep these stable and semantic.

```typescript
// ✅ ACCEPTABLE — stable, semantic selector with text scoping
this.page.locator("#menu a", { hasText: "About" });
this.page.locator("input#cardholder-name");

// ✅ ACCEPTABLE — testIdAttribute is "id", so getByTestId targets a stable id
this.page.getByTestId("g2599-name"); // equivalent to id="g2599-name"

// ❌ STILL BAD — dynamically generated IDs or positional selectors
this.page.locator("#random-abc123"); // runtime-generated ID
this.page.locator("input:nth-child(3)"); // positional
```

> Built-in locators are always preferred. Use `locator("#id")` only when the ID is stable (not runtime-generated) and no built-in alternative exists.

## 2. Define Locators as Class Properties

> Locators MUST be declared as `readonly` class properties and assigned in the constructor. Defining a locator inline inside a method body is discouraged — declare it as a field instead. This is the established pattern in `NavigationComponent.ts`.

```typescript
// ✅ PREFERRED — readonly fields declared at top, assigned in constructor
export class NavigationComponent extends BasePage {
  readonly aboutMenu: Locator;
  readonly searchInput: Locator;
  readonly homeLogo: Locator;

  constructor(page: Page) {
    super(page);
    this.aboutMenu = this.page.locator("#menu a", { hasText: "About" });
    this.searchInput = this.page.locator("#s");
    this.homeLogo = this.page.locator("a[title='GlobalSQA'] img");
  }

  async clickAboutMenu(): Promise<void> {
    await this.aboutMenu.click();
  }
}

// ❌ AVOID — locator defined inline inside a method body
async clickAbout(): Promise<void> {
  await this.page.locator("#menu a", { hasText: "About" }).click(); // declare as a field instead
}
```

> Specs read these locators directly for assertions (e.g. `await expect(navigation.homeLogo).toBeVisible()`), which is why they are `readonly` (publicly accessible) rather than `private`.

## 3. Use Arrow Functions for Dynamic (Parameterized) Locators

When a locator depends on a parameter, declare an arrow-function field assigned in the constructor instead of a method that returns a locator — keeps it lazy and consistent with static fields.

```typescript
// ✅ PREFERRED — declared at top, assigned in constructor (after static fields)
export class DriversPage extends BasePage {
  readonly submitButton: Locator;
  readonly driverRow: (index: number) => Locator;

  constructor(page: Page) {
    super(page);
    this.submitButton = this.page.getByRole("button", { name: "Submit" });
    this.driverRow = (index) => this.page.getByTestId(`driver-row-${index}`);
  }
}

// ❌ AVOID — method creates a new locator reference each call, less explicit
async getDriverByIndex(index: number) {
  return this.page.getByTestId(`driver-name-${index}`);
}
```

## 4. Chain Locators for Scoped Queries

Scope child locators to a parent to avoid ambiguous matches.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — child scoped to parent (BasePage.locateWithText does this)
locateWithText(selector: string, text: string) {
  return this.page.locator(selector).getByText(text, { exact: true });
}
```

## 5. No Hard-Coded Waits — Use Web-First Assertions

Never use `waitForTimeout`. Let Playwright's auto-waiting handle synchronization (`expect.timeout` is 15s in `playwright.config.ts`).

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
await page.getByRole("button", { name: "Submit" }).click();
await expect(page.getByText("Success")).toBeVisible();
await expect(page).toHaveURL(/\/about\/?$/);

// ❌ BAD
await page.click("button");
await page.waitForTimeout(3000);
```

## 6. Prefer Assertions Over Manual Retry Loops

Use web-first assertions (`expect(...).toBeVisible({ timeout })`, `.toBeHidden()`, `.toHaveText()`, etc.) instead of custom retry/polling wrappers.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
await expect(this.searchInput).toBeVisible({ timeout: 15_000 });
await this.searchInput.fill(text);

// ❌ BAD — custom retry inflates execution time and hides real errors
await retry(async () => {
  await this.searchInput.fill(text);
});
```

## 7. Separate Action and Assertion Methods

Keep page action methods and assertion methods distinct for readability and reuse (SRP). `NavigationComponent` follows this: `clickAboutMenu()` (action) vs `isMenuVisible()` (assertion).

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
async clickAboutMenu(): Promise<void> {
  await this.aboutMenu.click();
}

async isMenuVisible(): Promise<void> {
  await expect(this.aboutMenu).toBeVisible();
  await expect(this.searchInput).toBeVisible();
  await expect(this.homeLogo).toBeVisible();
}
```

## 8. Use Type-Safe Parameters with Interfaces

Accept typed data objects in page methods instead of long lists of individual string parameters. Data shapes belong in `data/types/` (e.g. `TestData`). `SamplePage.fillForm(name, email, website, ...)` is a good candidate to refactor toward this pattern.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
import { TestData } from "../data/types/TestData";

async fillForm(data: TestData) {
  await this.fillInput("#g2599-name", data.name);
  await this.fillInput("#g2599-email", data.email);
  await this.fillInput("#g2599-website", data.website);
}
```

## 9. Put Shared Interaction Helpers in `BasePage` (DRY)

This project has a real `BasePage` (`pages/base/BasePage.ts`) that all page objects extend. Page-agnostic interaction patterns (fill, toggle, dropdown, visibility assertions) belong there and accept a `Locator` or selector string as a parameter. Add new reusable helpers to `BasePage` rather than duplicating them across page objects.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — generic helper lives in BasePage, parameterized by locator/selector
async fillInput(inputField: Locator | string, text: string): Promise<void> {
  const target =
    typeof inputField === "string" ? this.page.locator(inputField) : inputField;
  await target.fill(text);
}

async selectOption(dropdown: Locator, option: string) {
  await dropdown.selectOption(option);
}
```

> `BasePage` re-exports `Page`, `Locator`, `expect`, and `Download` from `@playwright/test`, so page objects import them from `./base/BasePage`.

## 10. Compose Pages with Component Objects

Break large pages into focused component classes (which also extend `BasePage`) and expose them as fixtures. `NavigationComponent` is an example — a reusable navigation component used across specs.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — a focused component, registered as a fixture in tests/base/baseTest.ts
export class NavigationComponent extends BasePage {
  readonly aboutMenu: Locator;

  constructor(page: Page) {
    super(page);
    this.aboutMenu = this.page.locator("#menu a", { hasText: "About" });
  }

  async clickAboutMenu(): Promise<void> {
    await this.aboutMenu.click();
  }
}
```

## 11. Use Fixtures for Page Objects and Test Data

Instantiate page objects and load test data through Playwright fixtures in `tests/base/baseTest.ts`, then destructure them in specs. Don't `new` page objects inside spec bodies.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — fixture provides the page object; spec just uses it
export const test = baseTest.extend<{ samplePage: SamplePage }>({
  samplePage: async ({ page }, use) => {
    await use(new SamplePage(page));
  },
});

// in the spec
test("fill form", async ({ samplePage, testData }) => {
  await samplePage.goto();
  await samplePage.fillForm(testData);
});
```

Wrap distinct phases in `test.step()` for readable reports (see `sampleTest.spec.ts`, `navigationTest.spec.ts`).

## 12. Soft Assertions Are Allowed (Use Sparingly)

```typescript
// ✅ Hard assertion (default) — stops the test on first failure
await expect(this.page.getByText(data.name)).toBeVisible();

// ✅ Soft assertion — collects multiple failures, useful for verifying a whole form
await expect.soft(this.page.getByText(data.name)).toBeVisible();
await expect.soft(this.page.getByText(data.email)).toBeVisible();
await expect.soft(this.page.getByText(data.website)).toBeVisible();
```

> Default to hard `expect()`. Reach for `expect.soft()` only when checking a group of independent values where seeing every failure at once is more useful than failing fast.

## 13. POM Method Abstraction — Keep It Shallow (Max 2 Layers)

A page object method should be at most **two layers** deep:

| Layer       | Name          | Definition                                                                                   | Called by                       |
| ----------- | ------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| **Layer 1** | **Atomic**    | Directly interacts with a locator (click, fill, `expect`, etc.). No calls to other page-object methods. | Specs *or* Layer 2 methods      |
| **Layer 2** | **Composite** | Groups two or more Layer 1 calls to complete one logical action. Calls Layer 1 methods only. | Specs only                      |

Avoid a third layer (a composite calling another composite) — it hides what the test does and makes failures harder to diagnose.

```typescript
// ✅ LAYER 1 — atomic, directly on a locator
async clickAboutMenu(): Promise<void> {
  await this.aboutMenu.click();
}

// ✅ LAYER 2 — composite, groups Layer 1 calls
async searchFor(text: string): Promise<void> {
  await this.searchInput.fill(text);
  await this.searchInput.press("Enter");
}

// ❌ AVOID — Layer 3: composite calling another composite
async runFullNavigationFlow(): Promise<void> {
  await this.searchFor("about"); // composite calling composite
  await this.completeContactFlow(); // composite calling composite
}
```

> **Inherited `BasePage` helpers don't count as a layer.** Calling `this.fillInput(...)`, `this.selectOption(...)`, etc. is using a shared utility, not a page-object composition layer.

## Quick Reference

| Pattern             | Prefer                                                                 | Avoid                                            |
| ------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| Locators            | `getByRole`, `getByLabel`, `getByText`, `getByTestId` (= `id`)         | Brittle CSS, XPath, dynamic IDs                  |
| Generic locators    | Stable `locator("#id")` / `locator("sel", { hasText })` when needed    | Runtime-generated IDs, positional CSS            |
| Locator placement   | `readonly` field declared at top + assigned in constructor             | Inline locators inside method bodies             |
| Dynamic locators    | `readonly fn: (x) => Locator` assigned in constructor (after static)   | Methods that return a fresh locator              |
| Waiting             | `expect(...).toBeVisible()`                                            | `waitForTimeout`, custom retry loops             |
| Assertions          | Web-first `expect(locator).toHaveText()`                               | `textContent()` + manual checks                  |
| Soft assertions     | `expect.soft()` for multi-field checks (Playwright runner supports it) | Overusing soft asserts where fail-fast is better |
| Page params         | Typed interfaces (`data/types/`)                                       | Long lists of raw string args                    |
| Shared helpers      | Add to `BasePage`                                                      | Duplicating helpers across page objects          |
| Page objects        | Provide via fixtures in `tests/base/baseTest.ts`                       | `new`-ing page objects inside specs              |
| POM method depth    | Max 2 layers: atomic + composite                                       | Layer 3+ (composite calling composite)           |
